<section class="hidden" id="homography">
<div class="section-label">§ 04 — PROJECTION MATHEMATICS</div>
<h2>Homography &amp; Warping</h2>
<p class="sub">A homography is a 3×3 projective transformation matrix mapping points in one plane to another. It underpins every quad-based projection mapping system — from pinhole camera models to full 3D mesh warping pipelines.</p>
<div class="math-display">
<div class="eq">
<span class="comment">// Homogeneous point transformation</span><br/>
      [<span class="var">x'</span>, <span class="var">y'</span>, <span class="var">w'</span>] = <span class="var">H</span> · [<span class="var">x</span>, <span class="var">y</span>, 1]<br/><br/>
<span class="comment">// 3×3 Homography matrix H (8 degrees of freedom)</span><br/>
<span class="var">H</span> = | h₀₀  h₀₁  h₀₂ |<br/>
          | h₁₀  h₁₁  h₁₂ |<br/>
          | h₂₀  h₂₁   1  |<br/><br/>
<span class="comment">// Normalized output coordinates</span><br/>
<span class="var">xₒᵤₜ</span> = x' / w'<br/>
<span class="var">yₒᵤₜ</span> = y' / w'<br/><br/>
<span class="comment">// Solved via Direct Linear Transform (DLT) from 4 point correspondences</span><br/>
<span class="comment">// A · h = 0,  solve with SVD → smallest singular vector</span>
</div>
</div>
